AGI - Last March 31 elections dug a groove in Turkish politics. After 22 years the Akp of President Recep Tayyip Erdogan is no longer the first party of the country and does not rule in the five most populous cities, but also the collapse of the Kurdish thread party Dem and the growth of the ultra-conservative Islamic party Yeni Refah. A result that, beyond the criticisms suffered in recent years, confirms that Turkey is a country where the democratic process takes place regularly», people believe in the power of vote and representation.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In fact, despite the turn of 78.5% has been the lowest of the last 20 years, it remains a high figure. To keep so many voters away this time was the disappointment for the management of the economy. To make the idea of the size of participation just think that in the presidential elections of just 10 months ago the turnout was 87%, but two rounds of elections were needed to elect Erdogan, who at the ballot passed it with a relocated 52%, a percentage not sure 'bulgara', far from those of countries like Russia and Azerbaijan.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The heavy defeat suffered by Erdogan led to the growth of the Yeni Refah party, ultra-conservative Islamists who in 10 months doubled the votes and with 2.8 million preferences became the third party of the country. A success achieved through a campaign against Erdogan, accused of "solding Gaza to Israel" >, of not having intervened for Palestinians and not applying economic sanctions to Israel. He toured the web the advertisement where an Akp stamp became an Israeli flag. Refah accused Erdogan of having passed to politics of increasing interest cuts, theoretically not in line with religion, but also of having given too much space and freedom to the Lgbtq community and of having imposed the anti-Covid vaccine to the population.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
To the growth of Yeni Refah is corresponded the collapse of the Kurdish thread of Dem, acronym that replaced Hdp. Five years ago sided with the mayor of Istanbul Ekrem Imamoglu, this year the Dem presented a candidate that collected 2% of preferences. A vertical collapse compared to 8% obtained at the presidential elections 10 months ago in Istanbul itself. It is evident that the votes, despite the presence of a candidate, ended in the basket of Imamoglu, showed more concrete than the party itself. On a national scale the votes collected by the Kurdish philosophers were much less, the Dems passed from 8.8% last May to 5.7% present and are no longer the third party of the country.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

